+# LXCoordinateRemapOp Backend Prototype
+
+This patch/spec is keyed to Torch-Spyre `lx_coordinate_remap_v0` artifacts and
+the normalized `coordinate_remap.deeptools_dataop` payload.  It is meant to land
+as a Deeptools DataOp, not as another `STCDPOpLx` physicalizer patch.
+
+## Import Surface
+
+`LXCoordinateRemapOp` is accepted in a mixed SuperDSC `dataOpdscs_` row.  The
+consumer row must be scheduled after the remap row in `coreIdToDscSchedule`.
+
+```json
+{
+  "op": {"name": "LXCoordinateRemapOp"},
+  "schemaVersion": 0,
+  "sourceName": "buf0",
+  "producer": "buf0",
+  "consumer": "buf1",
+  "producerLxBase": 4096,
+  "consumerLxBase": 36864,
+  "coverage": {"device_sizes": [16], "status": "complete"},
+  "dependencyOrder": [
+    {"order": 0, "kind": "producer_lx_write_before_remap", "op": "buf0"},
+    {"order": 1, "kind": "coordinate_remap", "cellCount": 4},
+    {"order": 2, "kind": "consumer_lx_read_after_remap", "op": "buf1"}
+  ],
+  "lowering": {
+    "strategy": "explicit_lx_copy_via_l3",
+    "addressUnits": "bytes"
+  },
+  "movements": [
+    {
+      "moveIndex": 1,
+      "bytes": 8,
+      "source": {
+        "core": 1,
+        "logicalSlice": {"starts": {"d0_": 4}, "sizes": {"d0_": 4}},
+        "lxAddress": 4096,
+        "localByteRange": {"start": 0, "end": 8},
+        "lxByteRange": {"start": 4096, "end": 4104}
+      },
+      "destination": {
+        "core": 0,
+        "logicalSlice": {"starts": {"d0_": 4}, "sizes": {"d0_": 4}},
+        "lxAddress": 36872,
+        "localByteRange": {"start": 8, "end": 16},
+        "lxByteRange": {"start": 36872, "end": 36880}
+      }
+    }
+  ]
+}
+```
+
+## Validation
+
+The Deeptools importer should reject the data-op before DDC/DCG if any of the
+following is true:
+
+1. `op.name != "LXCoordinateRemapOp"` or `schemaVersion != 0`.
+2. `lowering.strategy != "explicit_lx_copy_via_l3"` or
+   `lowering.addressUnits != "bytes"`.
+3. Dependency kinds are not exactly:
+   `producer_lx_write_before_remap`, `coordinate_remap`,
+   `consumer_lx_read_after_remap`.
+4. Any movement has `bytes <= 0`, or its source/destination `lxByteRange`
+   length differs from `bytes`.
+5. Any source or destination `lxAddress` differs from its `lxByteRange.start`.
+6. Destination `localByteRange` entries overlap for the same destination core.
+7. Logical movement rectangles do not cover `coverage.device_sizes` exactly
+   once.  The first backend patch can implement this with the same rectangle
+   volume and pairwise-intersection checks Torch-Spyre performs.
+8. Any byte address falls outside the producer or consumer LX allocation
+   reported by the surrounding SuperDSC.
+
+## DCG Lowering
+
+For each movement, generate explicit traffic through L3:
+
+1. On `source.core`, issue an LX load from `source.lxAddress` for `bytes`.
+2. Store that payload to an L3 scratch slot assigned to `moveIndex`.
+3. Synchronize source L3 store before destination L3 load.
+4. On `destination.core`, load the same L3 scratch slot.
+5. Store to destination LX at `destination.lxAddress` for `bytes`.
+6. Synchronize the remap row before the consumer DL row.
+
+The prototype can be conservative:
+
+- Use one L3 scratch slot per movement.  Coalescing adjacent movements can come
+  later after value-correctness is established.
+- Preserve movement order by `moveIndex` to keep debug traces stable.
+- Generate only byte-contiguous copies at first.  Torch-Spyre already breaks
+  1-D and simple 2-D remaps into byte-contiguous movements.
+- Reject folded SuperDSC remap rows until the non-folded path is value-correct.
+
+## Required Deeptools Touch Points
+
+The sparse Deeptools source available for this iteration shows these seams:
+
+- `dxp/dxp.cpp::Dxp::runCodegen()` already selects
+  `DcgManager::runDcgForDataOpsDlOps()` when a mixed SuperDSC has both
+  `dataOpdscs_` and `dscs_` plus `coreIdToDscSchedule`.
+- `dcg/dcg_manager/dcg_manager.cpp::runDcgForDataOpsDlOps()` already compiles
+  scheduled DataOp rows before DL rows and merges row PCFGs with before/after
+  syncs.
+- `dcg/dcg_manager/dcg_manager.cpp::mergePcfgInSuperDSC()` already merges each
+  `DataOpDsc::pcfg_` row according to `coreIdToDscSchedule`.
+
+Therefore the first real patch should add:
+
+1. An `OpFuncs::LXCoordinateRemapOp` enum/string entry.
+2. An `LXCoordinateRemapOp` data structure with the movement fields above.
+3. JSON import/export for the data-op payload.
+4. A DCG frontend method that fills `DataOpDsc::pcfg_` with explicit
+   LXLU/L3SU/L3LU/LXSU copies.
+5. A `runDcgForDataOpsDlOps()` dispatch branch that calls the new frontend
+   method for this op before the generic DataOp path.
+
+## Expected Lowering Pseudocode
+
+```cpp
+void DcgFE::generatePcfgIRForLXCoordinateRemapOp(
+    SuperDsc& sdsc, DataOpDsc& ddsc, int uniqueId) {
+  auto* op = checked_cast<LXCoordinateRemapOp*>(ddsc.op);
+  validateLXCoordinateRemapOp(sdsc, *op);
+
+  ddsc.coreIdsUsed_.clear();
+  for (const auto& movement : op->movements) {
+    ddsc.coreIdsUsed_.insert(movement.source.core);
+    ddsc.coreIdsUsed_.insert(movement.destination.core);
+  }
+  ddsc.pcfg_.resize(ddsc.coreIdsUsed_.size());
+
+  for (const auto& movement : sortByMoveIndex(op->movements)) {
+    const auto l3Slot = allocateRemapL3Scratch(sdsc, ddsc, movement);
+
+    auto& sourcePcfg = pcfgFor(ddsc, movement.source.core);
+    emitLXToL3Copy(sourcePcfg,
+                   /*core=*/movement.source.core,
+                   /*lxByteAddress=*/movement.source.lxAddress,
+                   /*l3Scratch=*/l3Slot,
+                   /*bytes=*/movement.bytes);
+    emitRemapStoreSync(sourcePcfg, movement.moveIndex);
+
+    auto& destinationPcfg = pcfgFor(ddsc, movement.destination.core);
+    emitRemapLoadSync(destinationPcfg, movement.moveIndex);
+    emitL3ToLXCopy(destinationPcfg,
+                   /*core=*/movement.destination.core,
+                   /*l3Scratch=*/l3Slot,
+                   /*lxByteAddress=*/movement.destination.lxAddress,
+                   /*bytes=*/movement.bytes);
+  }
+}
+```
+
+The concrete `emitLXToL3Copy` and `emitL3ToLXCopy` helpers should reuse the
+same PCFG instruction builders used by STCDP/InputFetchNeighbor once the
+complete Deeptools headers are available.  The important semantic difference is
+that source and destination byte addresses are explicit; no overlap inference
+from producer and consumer pieces is performed.
